      "graph_rag": {
        "answer": "Sauti is the name by which the sage Ugrasrava, son of Lomaharshana, is known in the Mahabharata. He is described as \"well-versed in the Puranas\" and as the narrator who comes to the assembly of the Saunaka-sages in the forest of Naimisa after their twelve-year sacrifice. The sages, wishing to hear the great story, ask him what he will relate, and Sauti replies that he will recount the sacred history called Bharata (the Mahabharata) that was composed by Vyasa and recited by Vaisampayana. Thus, at the very opening of the work Sauti occupies the role of the principal storyteller who introduces and begins the narration of the Mahabharata for the assembled Munis. [chunk_002]",
